│ stop({"edit_points": [[2673, 2678,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.     │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation in InstCombine propagates the    │
│ sign argument through nested copysign calls: copysign(Mag, copysign(?, X)) -> │
│ copysign(Mag, X). This is generally correct semantically for IEEE-754, but it │
│ interacts incorrectly with fast-math flags. In the provided reproducer, the   │
│ outer copysign has the nnan flag (NoNaNs), meaning the instruction assumes    │
│ its operands and result are never NaN. The inner copysign shields the outer   │
│ from a NaN operand: copysign(y, z) produces a non-NaN result even if z is     │
│ NaN. After InstCombine replaces the sign operand with z directly, the nnan    │
│ constraint is violated when z is NaN, turning the result into poison, as      │
│ reported by Alive2.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows InstCombine     │
│ visiting the copysign intrinsic and applying the transformation:\n- IC: Mod = │
│ %r = call nnan nsz float @llvm.copysign.f32(float %x, float %s)\n- New = %r = │
│ call nnan nsz float @llvm.copysign.f32(float %x, float %z)\nIt also erases    │
│ the inner copysign %s. There is no change to fast-math flags and no analysis  │
│ indicating the sign operand is non-NaN. The AA report is unrelated. The       │
│ transformation point is visitCallInst in InstCombineCalls.cpp at the copysign │
│ case.\nThe Alive2 counterexample shows z = sNaN, x = +0, y = +0. Source       │
│ produces r = +0.0 (non-NaN), but target r is poison because nnan forbids NaN  │
│ operands/results and z is NaN as a direct operand. This confirms the          │
│ transformation increased poison potential.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe    │
│ InstCombine rule \"Propagate sign argument through nested calls\" in the      │
│ copysign handling does not consider fast-math NoNaNs on the outer call. In    │
│ LLVM, NoNaNs means the operation assumes inputs and the result are never NaN; │
│ using a NaN operand in an instruction marked nnan is undefined/poison. The    │
│ inner copysign produces a non-NaN value from a possibly NaN sign input.       │
│ Replacing the sign with the raw X can introduce a NaN operand to the nnan     │
│ outer copysign, breaking correctness. Therefore, the propagation must be      │
│ gated when the outer instruction has NoNaNs unless it can be proven the       │
│ propagated operand cannot be NaN.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:      │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp\n- Lines: 2673-2678\n-   │
│ Change: Modify the copysign propagation through nested calls to check         │
│ fast-math flags and known-NaN-ness before replacing the sign operand.         │
│ Specifically:\n  - If the outer copysign has NoNaNs                           │
│ (II->getFastMathFlags().noNaNs()), only perform the replacement when          │
│ isKnownNeverNaN(X, /*Depth=*/0, getSimplifyQuery().getWithInstruction(II)) is │
│ true.\n  - Otherwise, keep the existing behavior.\n\nSuggested code           │
│ adjustment:\n  // Propagate sign argument through nested calls:\n  //         │
│ copysign Mag, (copysign ?, X) --> copysign Mag, X\n  Value *X;\n  if          │
│ (match(Sign, m_Intrinsic<Intrinsic::copysign>(m_Value(), m_Value(X)))) {\n    │
│ // Beware of nnan: replacing Sign with X may introduce a NaN operand.\n    if │
│ (!II->getFastMathFlags().noNaNs() ||\n        isKnownNeverNaN(X, /*Depth=*/0, │
│ getSimplifyQuery().getWithInstruction(II)))\n      return replaceOperand(*II, │
│ 1, X);\n  }\n\nThis ensures we don't make the outer nnan instruction more     │
│ poisonous by introducing a potentially NaN operand.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe    │
│ bug stems from ignoring the NoNaNs fast-math flag when propagating the sign   │
│ operand through nested copysign calls. The fix is to guard the                │
│ transformation: only bypass the inner copysign when the outer instruction     │
│ does not have NoNaNs, or when analysis proves the propagated operand cannot   │
│ be NaN. This preserves correctness and prevents the transformation from       │
│ introducing poison in cases like the reproducer."})                           │
