│ (non-NaN), but target r is poison because nnan forbids NaN operands/results   │
│ and z is NaN as a direct operand. This confirms the transformation increased  │
│ poison potential.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe InstCombine rule            │
│ \"Propagate sign argument through nested calls\" in the copysign handling     │
│ does not consider fast-math NoNaNs on the outer call. In LLVM, NoNaNs means   │
│ the operation assumes inputs and the result are never NaN; using a NaN        │
│ operand in an instruction marked nnan is undefined/poison. The inner copysign │
│ produces a non-NaN value from a possibly NaN sign input. Replacing the sign   │
│ with the raw X can introduce a NaN operand to the nnan outer copysign,        │
│ breaking correctness. Therefore, the propagation must be gated when the outer │
│ instruction has NoNaNs unless it can be proven the propagated operand cannot  │
│ be NaN.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:                                │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp\n- Lines: 2673-2678\n-   │
│ Change: Modify the copysign propagation through nested calls to check         │
│ fast-math flags and known-NaN-ness before replacing the sign operand.         │
│ Specifically:\n  - If the outer copysign has NoNaNs                           │
