│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The transformation in InstCombine propagates the sign argument through nested │
│ copysign calls: copysign(Mag, copysign(?, X)) -> copysign(Mag, X). This is    │
│ generally correct semantically for IEEE-754, but it interacts incorrectly     │
│ with fast-math flags. In the provided reproducer, the outer copysign has the  │
│ nnan flag (NoNaNs), meaning the instruction assumes its operands and result   │
│ are never NaN. The inner copysign shields the outer from a NaN operand:       │
│ copysign(y, z) produces a non-NaN result even if z is NaN. After InstCombine  │
│ replaces the sign operand with z directly, the nnan constraint is violated    │
│ when z is NaN, turning the result into poison, as reported by Alive2.         │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The log shows InstCombine visiting the copysign intrinsic and applying the    │
│ transformation:                                                               │
│ - IC: Mod = %r = call nnan nsz float @llvm.copysign.f32(float %x, float %s)   │
│ - New = %r = call nnan nsz float @llvm.copysign.f32(float %x, float %z)       │
│ It also erases the inner copysign %s. There is no change to fast-math flags   │
│ and no analysis indicating the sign operand is non-NaN. The AA report is      │
│ unrelated. The transformation point is visitCallInst in InstCombineCalls.cpp  │
│ at the copysign case.                                                         │
│ The Alive2 counterexample shows z = sNaN, x = +0, y = +0. Source produces r = │
│ +0.0 (non-NaN), but target r is poison because nnan forbids NaN               │
│ operands/results and z is NaN as a direct operand. This confirms the          │
│ transformation increased poison potential.                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The InstCombine rule "Propagate sign argument through nested calls" in the    │
│ copysign handling does not consider fast-math NoNaNs on the outer call. In    │
│ LLVM, NoNaNs means the operation assumes inputs and the result are never NaN; │
│ using a NaN operand in an instruction marked nnan is undefined/poison. The    │
│ inner copysign produces a non-NaN value from a possibly NaN sign input.       │
│ Replacing the sign with the raw X can introduce a NaN operand to the nnan     │
│ outer copysign, breaking correctness. Therefore, the propagation must be      │
│ gated when the outer instruction has NoNaNs unless it can be proven the       │
│ propagated operand cannot be NaN.                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp                  │
│ - Lines: 2673-2678                                                            │
│ - Change: Modify the copysign propagation through nested calls to check       │
│ fast-math flags and known-NaN-ness before replacing the sign operand.         │
│ Specifically:                                                                 │
│   - If the outer copysign has NoNaNs (II->getFastMathFlags().noNaNs()), only  │
│ perform the replacement when isKnownNeverNaN(X, /*Depth=*/0,                  │
│ getSimplifyQuery().getWithInstruction(II)) is true.                           │
│   - Otherwise, keep the existing behavior.                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested code adjustment:                                                    │
│   // Propagate sign argument through nested calls:                            │
│   // copysign Mag, (copysign ?, X) --> copysign Mag, X                        │
│   Value *X;                                                                   │
│   if (match(Sign, m_Intrinsic<Intrinsic::copysign>(m_Value(), m_Value(X)))) { │
│     // Beware of nnan: replacing Sign with X may introduce a NaN operand.     │
│     if (!II->getFastMathFlags().noNaNs() ||                                   │
│         isKnownNeverNaN(X, /*Depth=*/0,                                       │
│ getSimplifyQuery().getWithInstruction(II)))                                   │
│       return replaceOperand(*II, 1, X);                                       │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures we don't make the outer nnan instruction more poisonous by       │
│ introducing a potentially NaN operand.                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The bug stems from ignoring the NoNaNs fast-math flag when propagating the    │
│ sign operand through nested copysign calls. The fix is to guard the           │
│ transformation: only bypass the inner copysign when the outer instruction     │
│ does not have NoNaNs, or when analysis proves the propagated operand cannot   │
│ be NaN. This preserves correctness and prevents the transformation from       │
│ introducing poison in cases like the reproducer.                              │
